'''Jona Lendering''' (born 29 October 1964 in [[Beneden-Leeuwen]], [[Gelderland]]) is a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[historian]] and the author of books on [[Ancient history|antiquity]], [[History of the Netherlands|Dutch history]] and modern [[management]]. He has an MA in history from [[Leiden University]] and an MA in Mediterranean culture from the [[Vrije Universiteit|Amsterdam Free University]],<ref name=about>{{cite web |title=About Jona Lendering |work=Livius |url=http://www.livius.org/contributor/jona-lendering/ |accessdate=24 November 2017}}</ref> taught history at the Free University, and worked as an [[archivist]] employed by the Dutch government,<ref>{{cite web |title=About Livius.org |work=Livius |url=http://www.livius.org/about.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040219193759/http://www.livius.org/about.html |archivedate=19 February 2004 |accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref> before becoming one of the founders of the history school Livius Onderwijs.<ref name=about/>

==Career and works==
Lendering's biography of [[Alexander the Great]] (''Alexander de Grote'') attempted to make greater use than earlier scholars of [[Achaemenid Empire|Persian]] and [[Babylonia]]n sources. For example, he argued from [[Babylonian astronomical diaries]] that [[Darius III of Persia]] was deserted by his troops when he faced Alexander at the [[Battle of Gaugamela]], rather than personally leading the retreat as reported by Greek sources.<ref name=stronk>{{cite web |author=Jan P. Stronk |url=http://ccat.sas.upenn.edu/bmcr/2005/2005-07-35.html |accessdate=2008-12-09 |title=Jona Lendering, ''Alexander de Grote. De ondergang van het Perzische rijk''. |date=July 2005 |work=Bryn Mawr Classical Review}}</ref> His work, "Alexander de Grote. De ondergang van het Perzische rijk" was described by ''Bryn Mawr Classical Review'' contributor Jan P. Stronk from the University of Amsterdam, as "clear and compelling" and "manifestly written for the general public"-and although not sharing Lendering's love for psychological profiles, Lendering's work may be regarded as an incentive for serious scholars looking to expand their knowledge of new sources of ancient history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bmcr.brynmawr.edu/2005/2005-07-35.html |title=Bryn Mawr Classical Review 2005.07.35 |publisher=Bmcr.brynmawr.edu |date=2009-04-03 |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref>

In a passage cited by one commentator as characteristic of recent unsympathetic interpretations of Alexander,<ref>{{cite news |author=Betsy Carpenter |date=November 14, 2004 |title=Alexander's new look |work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/culture/articles/041122/22alex.htm |accessdate=2008-11-27 }}</ref> Lendering argued that Alexander's respectful treatment of Darius' family was not just an act of chivalry but also a claim to be the "new king". ''Quality Non-Fiction from Holland'' called ''Alexander de Grote'' "fascinating" and highlighted Lendering's attention to non-Western evidence.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Jona Lendering, ''Alexander the Great'' (''Alexander de Grote''): The fall of the Persian Empire, 340–320 |journal=Quality Non-Fiction from Holland |year=2004 |url=http://www.nlpvf.nl/book/book2.php?Book=353 |accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> However, ancient historian Jan P. Stronk thought it clear from Lendering's book that these sources could at best illuminate specific details of Alexander's life.<ref name=stronk/>

Lendering's interest in using western sources in combination with eastern sources can also be discerned in his book on ancient Rome (''Stad in marmer''), in which he quoted hitherto neglected [[Talmud]]ic sources,{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} and especially in his book on the legacy of [[Babylon]] and the world of [[Islam]] to Medieval Europe, ''Vergeten erfenis''.

In the ''Bryn Mawr Classical Review'', Lendering's review of Kaveh Farrokh ''Shadows in the Desert: Ancient Persia at War'' was criticized as being "marred by a series of overt inaccuracies, misconceptions and mistakes with respect to the domain of ancient Iranian studies." Lendering was also described by the authors of the response as displaying "a consistent pattern of ignoring seminal works, journal publications, and research that contradict his points of view."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bmcr.brynmawr.edu/2009/2009-02-02.html |title=Bryn Mawr Classical Review 2009.02.02 |publisher=Bmcr.brynmawr.edu |date=2009-02-02 |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref>

In 2010, Lendering and Arjen Bosman published "De rand van het Rijk: de Romeinen en de Lage Landen."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bmcr.brynmawr.edu/2011/2011-12-02.html |title=Bryn Mawr Classical Review 2011.12.02 |publisher=Bmcr.brynmawr.edu |date=2011-12-03 |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref>

==Livius.org==
Since 1996, Lendering has maintained ''Livius'', a website containing numerous articles on ancient history. The site is divided into sections on specific regions&nbsp;– Anatolia, Persia, Greece, etc.&nbsp;– and an individual selection of topics is treated for each of these.<ref>{{cite web |author=Thomas Kiely |date=May 20, 2004 |title=Full record display for ''Livius : articles on ancient history'' |work=[[Intute]] |url=http://www.intute.ac.uk/artsandhumanities/cgi-bin/fullrecord.pl?handle=humbul11885 |accessdate=2009-04-14 }}</ref> The Mesopotamian section contains the recently discovered ''[[Babylonian Chronicles]] of the Hellenistic Period''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.livius.org/cg-cm/chronicles/chron00.html |title=Livius.org: Mesopotamian Chronicles |work= |accessdate=2009-01-22}}</ref><ref>VU University Amsterdam, Faculty of Arts, [http://www.let.vu.nl/en/about-the-faculty/academic-staff/staff-listed-alphabetically/staff-l-s/prof-dr-r-j-van-der-spek/index.asp Prof. Dr. R.J. (Bert) van der Spek]</ref>

==Livius Onderwijs==
Livius Onderwijs is an association of teachers interested in ancient Mediterranean societies. ("Onderwijs" is Dutch for "[[education]]".) The association is based in Amsterdam and among other services offers a series of lectures there and elsewhere.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://74.125.79.102/translate_c?hl=en&sl=nl&u=http://www.liviusonderwijs.nl/colleges.html&prev=/search%3Fq%3D%2522Livius%2BOnderwijs%2522%26num%3D100%26hl%3Den%26newwindow%3D1%26rlz%3D1C1CHMP_en-GBGB291%26sa%3DG&usg=ALkJrhj6EZldlvmFqIoPdW2Exx6NxEEZug |title=Livius Education: Colleges |work= |accessdate=2008-12-06}}</ref> It was founded in 2005 by Lendering and Marco Prins.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://74.125.79.102/translate_c?hl=en&sl=nl&u=http://www.liviusonderwijs.nl/wiezijnwij.html&prev=/search%3Fq%3D%2522Livius%2BOnderwijs%2522%26num%3D100%26hl%3Den%26newwindow%3D1%26rlz%3D1C1CHMP_en-GBGB291%26sa%3DG&usg=ALkJrhhbdvcrL5nUtkxTjtCgA2D_fo_oxw |title=Livius Education: Who are we? |work= |accessdate=2008-12-06}}</ref>

==Awards==
After the publication of Lendering's ''Spijkers op laag water'', a book highly critical about the shortcomings of modern classicists, archaeologists, and historians, the research school of Dutch classicists and historians awarded him their annual "Oikos publieksprijs", recognizing Lendering's contributions to explaining Antiquity to a larger audience.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uitgeverijathenaeum.nl/web/Artikel/Jona-Lendering-wint-de-OIKOS-publieksprijs-2010.htm |title=Jona Lendering wint de OIKOS publieksprijs 2010 |publisher=Uitgeverijathenaeum.nl |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004213351/http://www.uitgeverijathenaeum.nl/web/Artikel/Jona-Lendering-wint-de-OIKOS-publieksprijs-2010.htm |archivedate=2013-10-04 |df= }}</ref>

In 2011, he received the [[Nederlands Klassiek Verbond|NKV]] award for his book ''De rand van het rijk'' (later translated into English and published as ''Edge of Empire'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archeonet.be/?p=18241|title=ArcheoNet Vlaanderen|work= |accessdate=2014-10-25}}</ref>

==Selected works==
*''Het visioen van Constantijn'' (2018; "The vision of Constantine"), with Vincent Hunink, Utrecht: Uitgeverij Omniboek, {{ISBN|9789401913096}}
*(with Arjan Bosman) ''De Rand van het Rijk. De Romeinen en de Lage Landen'' (2010; "Edge of the Empire. The Romans and the Low Countries");
*''Spijkers op laag water. Vijftig misverstanden over de Oudheid'' (2009; "Fifty common errors about Antiquity");
*''Vergeten erfenis. Oosterse wortels van de westerse cultuur'' (2009; "Lost Legacy. Eastern Roots of Western Civilization");
*''Oorlogsmist. Veldslagen en propaganda in de Oudheid'' (2006; "Fog of War. Ancient Battles and Battle Narratives");
*''Polderdenken. De wortels van de Nederlandse overlegcultuur'' (2005; "The Roots of the Dutch Consensus Culture");
*''Alexander de Grote. De ondergang van het Perzische rijk,'' (2004, "Alexander the Great. The Demise of the Persian Empire");
*''Stad in marmer. Gids voor het antieke Rome aan de hand van tijdgenoten'' (2002; "The Marble City. Literary Travel Guide of Ancient Rome");
*''Archeologie van de futurologie'' (2000; "A History of Futurology");
*''De randen van de aarde. De Romeinen tussen Schelde en Eems'' (2000; "The Edges of the Earth. The Romans in the Low Countries");
*''Een interim-manager in het Romeinse Rijk. Plinius in Bithynië'' (1999; "An Interim-Manager in the Roman Empire. Pliny in Bithynia")

Lendering is a regular contributor to ''[[Ancient Warfare (magazine)|Ancient Warfare]]''; his books have been translated into [[Turkish language|Turkish]].

